<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="135" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1093,1875]" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1633,1659]" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[325,599,1633,1659]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hishimonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="knightiellus">
<emphasis box="[325,599,1633,1659]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">Hishimonus knightiellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was earlier described from Borneo, 
<collectingCountry box="[1024,1129,1633,1659]" name="Malaysia" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1144,1256,1633,1659]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1316,1383,1633,1659]" name="China" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">China</collectingCountry>
(the 
<typeStatus box="[151,199,1669,1695]" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">type</typeStatus>
was not examined in the present work). It is here recorded for the first time from 
<collectingCountry box="[1137,1195,1669,1695]" name="India" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">India</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[1210,1308,1669,1695]" country="India" name="Haryana" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">Haryana</collectingRegion>
). It closely resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Viraktamath &amp; Murthy" authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Anantha Murthy" authorityYear="2014" box="[271,658,1705,1731]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hishimonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spicans">
<emphasis box="[271,390,1706,1731]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">H. spicans</emphasis>
Viraktamath &amp; Murthy
</taxonomicName>
but can be distinguished in having the pygofer lobe with many stout macrosetae over the dorsocaudal quarter; aedeagal basal processes not widely splayed, closer to each other than to shaft, about half as long as shaft, with blunt ends; and gonopore subapical on ventral margin (Figs 16 – 18). We provide photographic illustrations which complement the earlier descriptions given by Viraktamath and Anantha Murthy (2014).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
